T1  - Black lives matter in the sports world
AN  - 2518072929
AB  - This issue explores the relationship between sports and BLM specifically and racial, gender and ethnic discrimination or challenges more generally. The contributors build from and extend the burgeoning academic scholarship on race, sport, and activism over the past decade, and ask critical questions about the current and future status of promoting racial justice within and through sport (Agyemang and Singer 2014; Coombs and Cassilo 2017; Darnell 2012; Evans et al. 2020; Gill 2016; Hylton 2020; Schmittel and Sanderson 2015). While debates around race relations in sport are not new, they have a renewed urgency and intensity due to BLM and the COVID-19 pandemic, shining a light on continued inequities and injustices in sport and society. Questions remain about how various actors within sport are responding to BLM. Debates about the efficacy of athlete activism, corporate messaging, league actions to redress racism, and media coverage continue. Indeed, they have extended internationally as individual athletes, governing bodies, clubs and teams around the world integrated BLM protests during the spring and summer of 2020 to show solidarity against structural racism.
